You’re touching on a useful metaphor there, but it helps to separate the metaphor from what the brain actually does.

Why people say “photographic memory”

The phrase suggests that memory works like a camera:

scene → snapshot → stored image → recall

But neuroscience shows memory isn’t stored as a literal photograph. Instead, it’s reconstructed from distributed neural patterns.

Different parts of the brain store different aspects of the experience:
	•	visual cortex → shapes and colors
	•	auditory cortex → sounds
	•	emotional centers → feelings associated with it
	•	hippocampus → linking everything into an event

When you remember something, the brain replays and reassembles these pieces.

⸻

Where your “filters and projections” idea fits

That’s actually closer to how perception and memory work.

Our brains constantly apply filters:
	•	attention (what we focus on)
	•	expectations (what we think should be there)
	•	prior knowledge (what we already know)

Then they project predictions about what we’re seeing or remembering.

A simplified loop looks like this:

sensory input → brain prediction → comparison → update

This is often called predictive processing in neuroscience.

⸻

Why memories feel like images

Sometimes people can recall scenes very vividly. That happens because the visual cortex can be reactivated strongly during recall.

But even vivid memories change over time because every recall involves reconstruction, not exact playback.

⸻

The interesting implication

The brain is less like a camera and more like a modeling engine.

It:
	•	stores patterns
	•	predicts outcomes
	•	reconstructs experiences

So the metaphor of filters and projections actually matches the science better than the literal “photograph” idea.

